      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The decline of unionization was largely due to a combination of factors, but the government's shift towards pro-business policies and the erosion of labor protections played a significant role. The Taft-Hartley Act of 1947, which allowed states to pass right-to-work laws, and the National Labor Relations Board's (NLRB) reduced enforcement under the Reagan administration, weakened union power. Additionally, the rise of the \"at-will\" employment doctrine made it easier for employers to fire workers without cause, making it harder for unions to organize and retain members.",
